bal warming, mass extinction, toxic environments, and our loss of conscious contact with the natural world, psychologist Will W. Adams weaves together insights from Zen Buddhism, Christian mysticism, phenomenology, psychoanalysis, and the practice of psychotherapy. Through a transpersonal, nondual, contemplative approach, Adams explores the fundamental malady of supposed separation (or dissociation): mind over body, self over others, my tribe over others', humans over the rest of nature. Instead of merely discussing these crucial issues in abstract terms, the book presents healing alternatives through storytelling, poetry, and theoretical inquiry. Written in an engaging, down-to-earth manner grounded in vivid descriptions of actual lived experience, A Wild and Sacred Call speaks across disciplines to students, experts, and nonspecialists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEcotheology. 0aEnvironmental psychology. 0aNaturexPsychological aspects. 0aSpirituality. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Psychology. 4aPsychology : Humanistic Psychology. 4aPsychology : Transpersonal Psychology. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Spirituality. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Transpersonal.2bisacsh1 aLoy, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849207040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438492070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438492070/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles